Section1.Para:
Figure 3a shows the XRD spectrum of the sample synthesized by the microwave heating method. The obtained XRD pattern of the as-grown products is indexed well with the monoclinic phase of CuO crystals (JCPDS 45-0937); the lattice parameters are a=4.685 Å, b=3.426 Å, c=5.130 Å, and β=99.55∘. Moreover, the dominant peak located at 53.5° is indexed to the (020) plane of CuO. The strong intensity of this peak shows that these CuO nanorods are well crystallized and [020] is the preferred growth direction. The weak peaks of the products located at 2θ values of 32.5°, 35.4°, and 38.7° are indexed as (



                  $\overline{1}10$
                ), (



                  $\overline{1}11$
                ), and (111) planes of CuO, respectively. Figure 3b shows the TEM image of the CuO nanorods. It is found that the sample consists of a large number of smaller nanorods with almost the same growth direction (Fig. 3b). The high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) image is shown in Fig. 3c, which is taken from the rectangle pointed out by ‘C’ in Fig. 3b. The typical distance of lattice fringes measured in the image is 0.275 nm, which is consistent with that of the (



                  $\overline{1}10$
                ) plane in the CuO monoclinic structure. Figure 3d shows the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern of the sample, which is taken from the area marked ‘D’ in Fig. 3b. It indicates that these nanorods are crystallized with preferred orientation of the [020] direction. 

                    Fig. 3

                      (a) XRD pattern, (b) TEM image of the sample; HRTEM image and SAED pattern of the CuO nanorod are shown in (c) and (d), which are taken from the areas indicated by ‘C’ and ‘D’ in (b), respectively

Magnetic anisotropy is frequently reported in 1D nanostructures, such as doped ZnO nanowires [25] and ferromagnetic Ni nanorods [26], etc. In general, it is believed that this anisotropy is associated with the easy axis of magnetization and/or shape anisotropy of 1D nanostructures. As to CuO, it is noted that bulk CuO is an AFM material. The ferromagnetism of nanosized CuO is usually explained by intrinsic defects [16], size effect [17], and the uncompensated exchange couplings at the surface of CuO nanostructures [18]. In our work, higher saturation magnetization was observed when a magnetic field is applied perpendicular rather than parallel to the nanorods. This indicates that the easy axis of the FM spin orders is different from the growth direction of the nanorods, i.e. [020]. As there is no crystal alignment around the radial direction, the spins contributing to the FM signals are believed to be randomly distributed along the radial direction. This means that the dominant growth direction [020] of these nanorods is the axis with rather weak FM magnetization. This peculiar phenomenon may come from the nature of the magnetization arrangement in CuO. It is known that most cuprates are built by assembly of 1D or two-dimensional (2D) Cu–O units. But CuO is a three-dimensional (3D) coupled spin system with rather strong exchange interactions along one direction of [



                  $10\overline{1}$
                ] [27]. The match of experimental result and Heisenberg-model susceptibilities suggests that CuO could be classified as strong 1D AFM spin chains along [



                  $10\overline{1}$
                ], with weak FM or AFM exchanges [28] along other directions. When the spin at the surface of CuO is unpaired, uncompensated exchange couplings at the surface of CuO nanostructures [18] are modulated with the easy axis of magnetization along the [



                  $10\overline{1}$
                ] chain, which is perpendicular to the growth direction [020] of these CuO nanorods. Though [020] is the dominant growth direction of those CuO nanorods, it becomes the axis with rather weak FM magnetization. So, we hold that the FM anisotropy of these CuO nanorods comes from the fact that the easy growth direction of these CuO nanorods is different from that of the magnetization. Thus, the vertically aligned nanorods enhance the FM magnetization perpendicular to the wire axis.
